# Section 2 — Step-by-Step Setup Guide (From Zero)

## 🛒 Part A: Hardware You Need

### Components List
| # | Component | Purpose | Approx. Cost (₹) |
|---|---|---|---|
| 1 | Raspberry Pi 4 (Model B 4GB RAM) | Main controller | ₹4,500 |
| 2 | Raspberry Pi v2 Camera Module | Captures road images for AI | ₹500–1,500 |
| 3 | UBlox NEO-M8N GPS Module with Ceramic Active Antenna | Reads real-time GPS coordinates | ₹800 |
| 4 | MPU-9250 9DOF IMU Sensor Module (3-Axis Accelerometer, Gyroscope & Magnetometer) | Road condition monitoring & motion tracking | ₹350 |
| 5 | Electronic Spices Active Alarm Buzzer Driver Module (3.3V–5V) | Alerts the driver with loud alarm | ₹50 |
| 6 | HP SD Card 64GB | Stores the Raspberry Pi OS & project files | ₹450 |
| 7 | 5V 3A Power Supply | Powers the Raspberry Pi | ₹300 |
| 8 | Rpi Shop Raspberry Pi 4 Case Model B | Protective enclosure for the Pi | ₹250 |
| 9 | Jumper Wires (Female-to-Female) | Connects everything | ₹50 |
| 10 | Breadboard (optional) | Easier prototyping | ₹60 |

---

## 🔌 Part B: Hardware Wiring (Pin Connections)

### UBlox NEO-M8N GPS Module → Raspberry Pi
| GPS Pin | Raspberry Pi Pin | Description |
|---|---|---|
| **VCC** | Pin 2 (5V) | Power supply (NEO-M8N requires 5V) |
| **GND** | Pin 6 (Ground) | Ground |
| **TX** | Pin 10 (GPIO 15 / RXD) | GPS transmits data → Pi receives |
| **RX** | Pin 8 (GPIO 14 / TXD) | Pi transmits → GPS receives |

### MPU-9250 IMU Sensor → Raspberry Pi (I2C)
| IMU Pin | Raspberry Pi Pin | Description |
|---|---|---|
| **VCC** | Pin 1 (3.3V) | Power supply (3.3V logic) |
| **GND** | Pin 9 (Ground) | Ground |
| **SDA** | Pin 3 (GPIO 2 / SDA) | I2C Data |
| **SCL** | Pin 5 (GPIO 3 / SCL) | I2C Clock |

### Electronic Spices Buzzer Module → Raspberry Pi
| Buzzer Pin | Raspberry Pi Pin | Description |
|---|---|---|
| **VCC** | Pin 4 (5V) | Module power supply |
| **GND** | Pin 6 (Ground) | Ground |
| **I/O (Signal)** | Pin 12 (GPIO 18) | Control signal (BCM pin 18) |

### Raspberry Pi v2 Camera
- Connect the ribbon cable to the Camera (CSI) port on the Raspberry Pi board

---

## 💻 Part C: Software Setup on the Raspberry Pi

### Step 1: Install Raspberry Pi OS
1. Download [Raspberry Pi Imager](https://www.raspberrypi.com/software/) on your PC
2. Insert the MicroSD card into your PC
3. Open Raspberry Pi Imager → Choose OS: **Raspberry Pi OS (64-bit)**
4. Click the ⚙️ gear icon:
   - Set hostname: `roadguard`
   - Enable SSH: ✅
   - Set username: `pi`, password: `your_password`
   - Configure WiFi: Enter your WiFi name and password
5. Click **Write** → wait for it to finish
6. Insert the MicroSD card into the Raspberry Pi and power it on

### Step 2: Enable Interfaces
1. Open a terminal on the Pi (or SSH into it: `ssh pi@roadguard.local`)
2. Run:
   ```bash
   sudo raspi-config
   ```
3. Go to **Interface Options** and enable:
   - ✅ **Camera** (for Pi Camera v2)
   - ✅ **I2C** (for MPU-9250 IMU sensor)
   - ✅ **Serial Port** — say "No" to login shell, say "Yes" to hardware serial
4. Reboot:
   ```bash
   sudo reboot
   ```

### Step 3: Copy Project Files to the Raspberry Pi
From your PC, copy the `raspberry_pi/` folder to the Pi:

**Option A — Using USB Drive:**
1. Copy the entire `raspberry_pi/` folder onto a USB drive
2. Plug it into the Raspberry Pi
3. Open the file manager, copy the folder to `/home/pi/roadguard/`

**Option B — Using SCP (from your PC terminal):**
```bash
scp -r "C:\Users\DELL\OneDrive\Desktop\Pothole\raspberry_pi\*" pi@roadguard.local:/home/pi/roadguard/
```

### Step 4: Install Python Dependencies
On the Raspberry Pi terminal:
```bash
cd /home/pi/roadguard
pip install -r requirements.txt
```

> **Note**: `ultralytics` (YOLOv8) is a large package and may take 10–15 minutes to install on a Raspberry Pi.

### Step 5: Download the YOLOv8 Model
The first time you run the system, it will auto-download `yolov8n.pt` (~6MB). Or you can pre-download it:
```bash
cd /home/pi/roadguard
python -c "from ultralytics import YOLO; YOLO('yolov8n.pt')"
```

> **Important**: The default `yolov8n.pt` is a general-purpose model. For best pothole detection, you should train a custom model on pothole images and replace the `.pt` file.

### Step 6: Edit the Configuration
Open `config.py` and change:
```python
API_BASE_URL = "http://YOUR_LAPTOP_IP:5000/api"
```
Replace `YOUR_LAPTOP_IP` with the actual IP address of the laptop running the Flask server (e.g., `192.168.1.5`).

To find your laptop's IP:
- **Windows**: Open CMD → type `ipconfig` → look for "IPv4 Address" under your WiFi adapter
- Both Pi and Laptop must be on the **same WiFi network**

---

## 💻 Part D: Software Setup on Your Laptop (Server + Dashboard)

### Step 1: Install Python 3
Download and install [Python 3.10+](https://www.python.org/downloads/) if not already installed.

### Step 2: Install Server Dependencies
Open a terminal/command prompt:
```bash
cd "C:\Users\DELL\OneDrive\Desktop\Pothole\server"
pip install -r requirements.txt
```

### Step 3: Start the Flask Server
```bash
cd "C:\Users\DELL\OneDrive\Desktop\Pothole\server"
